# [<ticket #>] <type>: <subject> (Why is this change necessary?)
# <---------- Maximum of 50 Characters --------->|


# <--------------- Limit each line to less than 80 characters --------------->|
# How does the commit address the issue?

# Describe any side effects of this change.

# Provide links or keys to any relevant tickets or other sources of information
# Examples: "Closes issue #1234" or "Jira issue [NET-1234]"
#
# --- COMMIT END ---
# Type:
#   chore    (updating grunt tasks etc; no production code change)
#   docs     (changes to documentation)
#   feat     (new feature)
#   fix      (bug fix)
#   refactor (refactoring production code)
#   rem      (remove feature)
#   style    (formatting, missing newline, etc; no code changes)
#   test     (adding ro refactoring tests; no production change)
#   wip      (work in progress commit to be squashed -- **do not push!**)
# ------------------
# Reminders:
#   - Capitalize the subject line
#   - Do not end the subject line with a period
#   - Separate subject from body with a blank line
#   - Use the body of the commit to explain what and why, not how
#   - Can create bullet points in the body with "-"
# ------------------
# "wip" commit:
#   A wip commit should only happen on a local branch. These commits are for
#   unfinished snapshots that should not be checked into a shared branch.
#   Before pushing to a shared branch, ensure the wip commits are squashed.
